# Decision 1 — Why Did We Choose Star Schema? ⭐⭐⭐

Interviewer may ask:

> “Why not normalized schema?”

---

# Your Answer

We chose:

# Star Schema

because warehouse workloads are:

* analytical
* aggregation-heavy
* read-intensive

Star schema:

* reduces joins
* simplifies queries
* improves BI performance

---

# Important Insight ⭐

OLTP systems optimize:

```text id="m4v8qx"
writes + integrity
```

Warehouses optimize:

```text id="x7k2pn"
reads + analytics
```

That distinction is critical.

---

# Interview-Level Statement ⭐⭐⭐

```text id="r5n9yt"
Star schema improves analytical query performance by reducing join complexity and simplifying aggregation workloads.
```

Very strong answer.

---

# Decision 2 — Why FACT_SALES At Center? ⭐⭐⭐

Because:

# sales transaction

is core measurable business event.

Warehouse revolves around:

* business processes
* measurable metrics

---

# Important Principle ⭐

Fact tables store:

* measurable events

Dimensions store:

* descriptive context

---

# Interview Question

> “Why is revenue stored in fact table?”

---

# Correct Answer

Because:

```text id="u2m7vz"
revenue is additive business measure
```

Fact tables store:

* measures
* metrics
* numerical aggregations

---

# Decision 3 — Why Did We Choose This Grain? ⭐⭐⭐

Very important.

Our grain:

```text id="w8p1qr"
One row per product per order
```

---

# Why This Grain Is Powerful

Supports:

* product analytics
* basket analysis
* category trends
* flexible aggregations

---

# Example

If order has:

* 2 phones
* 1 charger

We can analyze products independently.

---

# Interview Insight ⭐⭐⭐

Bad grain selection destroys warehouse flexibility.

Extremely important statement.

---

# Common Interview Follow-Up

> “What happens if grain is too high?”

---

# Answer

High-level grain:

* loses analytical detail
* reduces flexibility
* limits drill-down analysis

---

# Decision 4 — Why SCD Type 2 For Customer? ⭐⭐⭐

Customer attributes change:

* city
* segment
* membership level

Business may want:

* historical tracking

Example:

```text id="k3x6mn"
customer moved from Mumbai -> Bangalore
```

Type 2 preserves history.

---

# Important Interview Insight ⭐⭐⭐

SCD Type 2 is preferred when historical business analysis matters.

Very strong statement.

---

# Common Interview Question

> “Why not Type 1?”

---

# Answer

Type 1 overwrites history.

Business loses historical reporting capability.

---

# Decision 5 — Why Partition FACT_SALES By Date? ⭐⭐⭐

Because:

* fact table grows continuously
* most analytical queries are time-based

Example:

* monthly revenue
* quarterly growth
* yearly trends

---

# Important Performance Insight ⭐⭐⭐

Partitioning reduces scanned data volume.

---

# Interview-Level Answer

```text id="v6r2py"
Partitioning FACT_SALES by order_date improves query performance through partition pruning.
```

Excellent technical answer.

---

# Decision 6 — Why Use CDC + Incremental Loading? ⭐⭐⭐

Because:

* full reloads do not scale

Imagine:

* billions of rows
* only few records changed

Incremental loading:

* reduces compute cost
* improves freshness
* improves scalability

---

# Important Interview Statement ⭐⭐⭐

```text id="p4w7zc"
CDC captures changed records while incremental pipelines process only delta data.
```

Strong DE answer.

---

# Decision 7 — Why Staging Layer Exists? ⭐⭐⭐

Very important architecture question.

---

# Correct Answer

Staging layer isolates:

* raw ingestion
* malformed records
* duplicates
* schema inconsistencies

before transformation.

---

# Important Insight ⭐

Production warehouses rarely load source data directly into warehouse tables.

Very important statement.

---

# Decision 8 — Why Data Quality Rules Needed? ⭐⭐⭐

Because:
bad data causes:

* incorrect KPIs
* broken dashboards
* business mistrust

---

# Example

Duplicate order rows:

```text id="n9q3vx"
double revenue calculation
```

Very dangerous.

---

# Decision 9 — Why Separate Dimensions? ⭐⭐⭐

Instead of storing:

* customer_name
* city
* category

inside fact table.

---

# Because

Dimensions:

* reduce redundancy
* improve maintainability
* support reusable analytics

---

# Interview-Level Architecture Thinking ⭐⭐⭐

Warehouse design is always balancing:

| Goal                | Tradeoff    |
| ------------------- | ----------- |
| Performance         | Storage     |
| Flexibility         | Complexity  |
| Historical tracking | ETL cost    |
| Simplicity          | Scalability |

This is real architecture thinking.

